.SH NAME
Element.ariaModal \- Element: ariaModal property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]ariaModal\f[B]\f[R] property of the \f[CR]Element\f[R]
interface reflects the value of the \f[CR]aria\-modal\f[R] attribute,
which indicates whether an element is modal when displayed.
Applying the \f[CR]aria\-modal\f[R] property to an element with
\f[CR]role=\(dqdialog\(dq\f[R] replaces the technique of using
aria\-hidden on the background for informing assistive technologies that
content outside a dialog is inert.
.SH VALUE
A string with one of the following values:
.TP
\f[B]\(dqtrue\(dq\f[R]
The element is modal.
.TP
\f[B]\(dqfalse\(dq\f[R]
The element is not modal.
.SH EXAMPLES
In this example the \f[CR]aria\-modal\f[R] attribute on the element with
an ID of \f[CR]address\-modal\f[R] is set to \(lqtrue\(rq indicating
that this is a modal dialog.
Using \f[CR]ariaModal\f[R] we update the value to \(lqfalse\(rq.
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]div\f[R]
  role=\(dqdialog\(dq
  id=\(dqaddress\-modal\(dq
  aria\-labelledby=\(dqdialog1Title\(dq
  aria\-describedby=\(dqdialog1Desc\(dq
  aria\-modal=\(dqtrue\(dq></\f[B]div\f[R]>
.EE
.IP
.EX
\f[B]let\f[R] el = document.getElementById(\(dqaddress\-modal\(dq);
console.log(el.ariaModal); \f[I]// \(dqtrue\(dq\f[R]
el.ariaModal = \(dqfalse\(dq;
console.log(el.ariaModal); \f[I]// \(dqfalse\(dq\f[R]
.EE
